  <h1>Common Late-Pay Misconceptions</h1>
  <p>Both vendors and customers — and employees and employers — commonly misunderstand late-payment rules. Getting these wrong costs money in both directions: vendors who don't enforce their contract terms leave money on the table; customers who believe they have protections they don't lose disputes they could have won. Here are the most frequent wrong beliefs.</p>
  <p><em>Written by Emerson Park (EP), Contributing Writer — State Wage Codes, Paralegal (employment). Updated May 2026.</em></p>

  <h2>"I can charge any late fee I want"</h2>
  <p><strong>Wrong.</strong> Two limits apply. First, state usury laws cap interest rates — even contractually agreed ones. While many states allow commercial parties to agree to higher rates than the statutory default, there is still a ceiling. Exceed it and you may forfeit all interest (in some states) or just the excess (in most). Second, courts apply the liquidated-damages doctrine: a late fee that's unreasonably large compared to the actual harm from late payment may be unenforceable as a "penalty." A $500/day late fee on a $200 invoice would almost certainly be struck down. The fee should be a reasonable pre-estimate of harm, not a punitive charge.</p>

  <h2>"If my contract doesn't mention late fees, I can't charge any"</h2>
  <p><strong>Mostly wrong.</strong> A silent contract doesn't bar you from recovering interest in a collection action — it just means you get the state's statutory commercial rate rather than a contractually negotiated one. In California, that's 10% per year (Cal. Civ. Code § 3289). In New York, 9% (CPLR § 5004). In Texas, 18% for written contracts (Tex. Fin. Code § 302.002). What you can't do is invoice for a late fee on the invoice itself without contractual authority — but when you sue or send to collections, statutory interest is recoverable. Not as good as having it in writing, but not zero either.</p>

  <h2>"Late fees become part of the invoice automatically"</h2>
  <p><strong>Wrong.</strong> Late fees don't self-execute. They must be disclosed in your contract or invoice terms before the work is done, properly invoiced when they accrue, and supported by contractual or statutory authority. Surprise additions to a past-due invoice — especially ones the customer never agreed to — typically don't bind the customer. If you want late fees, include them in your original contract and quote them on every invoice so there's no dispute that the customer was on notice.</p>

  <h2>"If my employer is one day late, I get the waiting time penalty"</h2>
  <p><strong>Depends heavily on state and circumstances.</strong> California's waiting-time penalty (Labor Code § 203) does trigger promptly for involuntary terminations — if the employer doesn't have the check ready on your last day, the clock starts immediately. But the penalty applies when the employer "willfully" fails to pay — a genuine, bona-fide good-faith dispute about the amount owed can stop the waiting-time clock from running. And in most other states, there's no equivalent day-one penalty. Florida has no state penalty at all. Texas requires "willful" violation and the penalty is capped. Illinois uses a percentage-per-day formula. The answer is almost entirely state-specific — check your state's actual statute.</p>

  <h2>"My employer can pay me with anything as long as it's something"</h2>
  <p><strong>Generally wrong.</strong> Nearly every state has a wage-payment statute that specifies acceptable payment forms: cash, check, direct deposit, or prepaid debit card (with conditions). Goods, scrip, company stock, store credit, or bartered services don't satisfy wage-payment obligations under most state laws. If an employer pays with non-cash equivalents and the employee later files a wage claim, those "payments" typically don't offset the wage liability. This rule matters most in cash-poor startups (equity doesn't substitute for wages owed) and in certain agricultural or service contexts.</p>

  <h2>"I'm a contractor, so wage payment rules don't apply"</h2>
  <p><strong>Right, but the alternative remedies are real.</strong> Independent contractors aren't covered by state wage-payment statutes — those only apply to employees. But contractors aren't without recourse for nonpayment. Contract law gives you breach-of-contract and unjust-enrichment claims. If a client doesn't pay, you can sue for the unpaid amount plus contractual interest and, if your contract says so, attorney's fees. The remedies differ from employee wage claims (no treble damages, no state labor agency, no mandatory fee-shifting), but you're not helpless. And note: if you think you were misclassified as a contractor when you should have been an employee, that's a separate claim worth consulting an attorney about.</p>

  <h2>"Compound interest is standard for late fees"</h2>
  <p><strong>Wrong.</strong> Simple interest is the universal default in late-fee calculations. Courts expect it; contracts that are ambiguous about compounding are interpreted to mean simple interest. Compound interest — where accrued interest is added to principal and future interest is calculated on the enlarged balance — requires explicit contractual language and faces additional scrutiny under usury law, because compounding pushes the effective annual rate above the stated nominal rate. Our calculator uses simple interest only. If you've been quoted a compound-interest late-fee structure, that's unusual and worth careful review.</p>

  <h2>"I can demand the entire late fee in one shot"</h2>
  <p><strong>Depends on the contract language.</strong> Some contracts impose a flat late fee at the trigger point and stop there — if your invoice says "$50 late fee if more than 30 days past due," you get $50 once, not more. Others accrue daily interest indefinitely until paid. Still others have a trigger fee plus interest. Read your specific contract. If you're drafting contracts, be explicit about whether the late charge is a one-time fee, daily accruing interest, or both — ambiguous language gets construed against the drafter in most states.</p>

  <h2>"State usury laws cap all late fees"</h2>
  <p><strong>Mostly wrong for commercial transactions.</strong> Many states exempt commercial transactions from their general usury limits entirely, or set much higher caps for business-to-business deals. Consumer transactions face stricter protection — credit card rates, personal loans, and consumer installment sales have tighter ceilings. But a commercial late-fee clause between two businesses operates in a different regulatory space. The specific cap depends on the parties (business vs. consumer), the type of transaction (loan vs. sale of goods vs. services), and sometimes the amount. If you're doing B2B commercial work, the usury ceiling is likely higher than you think.</p>

  <h2>"If the customer disputes the invoice, I can't charge late fees"</h2>
  <p><strong>Depends on the nature and timing of the dispute.</strong> A legitimate, timely, good-faith dispute about the amount owed can pause late-fee accrual on the disputed portion in many states. The operative words are "legitimate," "timely," and "good faith." A customer who waits until the due date — or past it — to raise an objection they knew about weeks ago is not acting in good faith. A customer who manufactures a dispute to avoid paying a bill they owe doesn't get the benefit of a dispute exception. A customer who raises a genuine issue promptly may. Courts look at whether the dispute was real or pretextual, and whether it was raised before the debt became overdue.</p>

  <h2>"If I can prove the debt, I'll automatically win in court"</h2>
  <p><strong>Proving the debt is necessary but not sufficient.</strong> You also need to show: the late fee was disclosed before the contract was formed; the rate is within your state's usury cap for this type of transaction; the fee is a reasonable estimate of harm and not an unenforceable penalty; and you've calculated interest correctly (simple, not compound, on the right principal, from the right start date). Courts also look at whether the defendant had proper notice of the late-fee terms, whether any statute of limitations has run, and whether the amount claimed matches the supporting documentation. Win the merits, lose on a calculation error or missing exhibit, and you may get less than you claimed.</p>

  <h2>"Waiting-time penalties don't apply to exempt employees"</h2>
  <p><strong>Wrong in California, nuanced elsewhere.</strong> California Labor Code § 203 applies to all employees — exempt and non-exempt alike. An exempt salaried manager fired on a Friday is still entitled to their final paycheck immediately. The "exempt" classification only affects overtime eligibility, not the final-paycheck obligation or the waiting-time penalty. In other states, verify whether the wage-payment statute specifies exemptions — some do, most don't for final-paycheck purposes.</p>
